## How it fits together – a tiny example

```ocaml
(* pcapng.ml – thin wrapper around the C primitives *)
type t = private unit   (* abstract, real type lives in the C stub *)
type frame = {
  timestamp    : float;
  captured_len : int;
  orig_len    : int;
  data        : bytes;
}
exception Error of string

external open_file : string -> t = "caml_pcapng_open_file"
external close     : t -> unit = "caml_pcapng_close"
external iter      : t -> (frame -> unit) -> unit = "caml_pcapng_iter"
external next      : t -> frame option = "caml_pcapng_next"
external fold      : t -> ('a -> frame -> 'a) -> 'a -> 'a = "caml_pcapng_fold"

let () = Callback.register_exception "Pcapng.Error" (Error "")
```

```ocaml
(* usage.ml – user code that processes each packet *)
let () =
  let rdr = Pcapng.open_file "sample.pcapng" in
  (* per‑frame callback – analogous to pandas.apply or Polars.map *)
  Pcapng.iter rdr (fun frame ->
      Printf.printf "ts=%.6f  cap=%d  orig=%d  data=%d bytes\n%!"
        frame.timestamp frame.captured_len frame.orig_len (Bytes.length frame.data)
    );
  Pcapng.close rdr
```

Running `ocamlopt -o usage unix.cma pcapng.cma usage.ml && ./usage` will print one
line per packet, exactly as a row‑wise API would do.

---

### TL;DR – What you get

| Feature | OCaml side | Implementation |
|---------|------------|----------------|
| **Open/close** a pcap‑ng file | `open_file`, `close` | C++ `Reader` object stored in a custom block |
| **Iterate with a callback** (row‑wise) | `iter` | C++ loop → OCaml `frame` record → `caml_callback_exn` |
| **Pull‑based alternative** | `next` | Returns `Some frame` or `None` |
| **Fold** (reduce) | `fold` | Re‑uses the iterator internally |
| **Error handling** | `Error of string` exception | C++ `try/catch` → `raise_error` → OCaml exception |
| **Memory safety** | All OCaml values are copied (`bytes`) | No raw pointers escape the stub; finaliser frees the C++ object |

Feel free to adapt the wrapper class (`pcapng_binding::Reader`) to the exact API
exposed by your version of `libpcapng`.  The rest of the glue code stays the
same. Happy hacking!
